label: Dehydration, caregiver report
definition: Participant's dehydration level, as reported by the mother. No dehydration was defined as: non-sunken eyes, no lethargy, easily consoled if irritable, drinks or breastfeeds well, normal abdominal skin pinch. Some dehydration was defined as: irritable/difficult to console, delay in skin pinch return, eyes sunken, when offered liquid drinks eagerly/demonstrates greater than normal thirst. Severe dehydration was defined as: lethargy, sunken eyes, listless, difficulty in mother/child interaction. If the mother reported severe dehydration, the participant was referred to the nearest health center for assessment and treatment. Surveillance was conducted twice weekly for up to 3 years of age to assess illness on all days since the last surveillance visit.
codebook_description: Maternal report of dehydration (None=0, Some=1, Severe=2), original SAF data | Was children dehydrated? Maternal report of dehydration. From illness dataset. Source=illnessfull.csv. 1=yes;0=no

label: L:M excretion test 1 day before stool collection
definition: Flag if the lactulose:mannitol test was given the day of or the day before the date of stool collection. First monthly asymptomatic stool samples should not have been collected within 48hrs after administration of the Lactulose:Mannitol (L:M) solution as it interferes with the gut inflammation biomarker assays. Whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day, diarrheal stool samples were collected before the end of the episode. First monthly asymptomatic stool samples were collected every month from 0-24 months of age, with a possible extension to 36 months of age. First monthly asymptomatic stool samples collected at 1-12, 15, 18, 21, and 24 months of age were included in analyses of gut function.
codebook_description: indicator if lactulose:mannitol test given the day of or the day before the date of stool collection. Source=UCF. 1= lm test done day of or day before; na=no proximate lm test

label: Cumulative sum atypical EPEC-pos stools
definition: Cumulative sum of stool samples positive for atypical Enteropathogenic Escherichia coli (EPEC) by PCR to date per participant. Atypical EPEC was defined as the presence of the eae virulence gene alone (in the absence of bfpA, stx1, or stx2). Whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day, diarrheal stool samples were collected before the end of the episode. Work up for detection of enteric pathogens was performed on the first stool sample collected during each diarrheal episode until 24 months of age (with a possible extension to 36 months of age) and on first monthly asymptomatic stool samples collected at 1-12, 15, 18, 21, and 24 months of age (with the option to test additional monthly stool samples to 36 months of age).

Whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day, diarrheal stool samples were collected before the end of the episode. Work up for detection of enteric pathogens was performed on the first stool sample collected during each diarrheal episode until 24 months of age (with a possible extension to 36 months of age) and on first monthly asymptomatic stool samples collected at 1-12, 15, 18, 21, and 24 months of age (with the option to test additional monthly stool samples to 36 months of age).
codebook_description: Did this stool sample have a parasite detected?. if alumb=1 or bcoli=1 or cmes=1 or crypt=1 or cyclo=1 or ehist=1 or enana=1 or everm=1 or giard=1 or hdim=1 or hnana=1 or hook=1 or ibut=1 or isos=1 or sstero=1 or schist=1 or atric=1 or taenia=1 then parasite =1; else parasite=0;. definition: Type of stool type collected, using information from surveillance. 'Diarrhea stools' were samples where diarrhea was reported within +/- 2 days of stool collection. Surveillance was conducted twice weekly for up to 3 years of age to assess illness on all days since the last surveillance visit. Whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day, diarrheal stool samples were collected before the end of the episode. codebook_description: Type of stool sample collected. Using information from surveillance. Diarrhea stool = diarrhea reported within +/- 2 days from stool collection. Monthly stool is stool collected more than 14 days away from study defined diarrhea. Source=Calculated. m1 =monthly; d1=diarrhea

label: Stool type
definition: Type of stool type collected, using information from surveillance. 'Diarrhea stools' were samples where diarrhea was reported within +/- 2 days of stool collection. Surveillance was conducted twice weekly for up to 3 years of age to assess illness on all days since the last surveillance visit. Whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day, diarrheal stool samples were collected before the end of the episode. Work up for detection of enteric pathogens was performed on diarrheal stool samples collected until 24 months of age (with a possible extension to 36 months of age) and on first monthly asymptomatic stool samples collected at 1-12, 15, 18, 21, and 24 months of age (with the option to test additional monthly stool samples to 36 months of age).

definition: Results of Astrovirus ELISA for this stool sample. Whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day, diarrheal stool samples were collected before the end of the episode. label: Stool type, severe diarrhea
definition: Type of stool type collected, using information from surveillance. 'Diarrhea stools' were samples that had a 'Diarrhea severity score' of at least 5 reported within +/- 2 days of stool collection. 'Monthly stools' were collected more than 2 days away from an episode of study-defined diarrhea. Surveillance was conducted twice weekly for up to 3 years of age to assess illness on all days since the last surveillance visit. Whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day, diarrheal stool samples were collected before the end of the episode. Work up for detection of enteric pathogens was performed on diarrheal stool samples collected until 24 months of age (with a possible extension to 36 months of age) and on first monthly asymptomatic stool samples collected at 1-12, 15, 18, 21, and 24 months of age (with the option to test additional monthly stool samples to 36 months of age).
codebook_description: Type of stool sample collected. Using information from surveillance. Diarrhea stool = diarrhea reported within +/- 2 days from stool collection plus having a diarrhea severity score of >= 5. Monthly stool is stool collected more than 2 days away from study defined diarrhea. Source=Calculated. m1 =monthly; d1=diarrhea  plus having a diarrhea severity score of >= 5

label: Rotavirus, by ELISA result
definition: Results of Rotavirus ELISA for this stool sample. Whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day, diarrheal stool samples were collected before the end of the episode. Work up for detection of enteric pathogens was performed on the first stool sample collected during each diarrheal episode until 24 months of age (with a possible extension to 36 months of age) and on first monthly asymptomatic stool samples collected at 1-12, 15, 18, 21, and 24 months of age (with the option to test additional monthly stool samples to 36 months of age).
codebook_description: Rotavirus result. Raw variable from FVF form. Use collapsed variable of ''rota'' for results. Added the response category of ''00'' for those samples which had a positive test result but stool collection occurred less than 28 days from rotavirus vaccination; these samples are deemed negative for rotavirus.. Source=FVF. positive results that occurred within 28d of the child receiving a rotavirus vaccination (positive test but rotavius negative)=00; positive =01; negative =02; indeterminate =03

label: Stature, 3rd
definition: Measurement #3 of the stature of the target child participant, in cm. Stature was measured as either recumbent length or height while standing. A 3rd measurement was only taken if the difference between measures 1 & 2 was greater than or equal to 0.5 cm. Anthropometry of target children was assessed 1 year after intervention initiation (midline, when target children were 8-15m of age) and 2 years after intervention initiation (endline, when target children were 21-27m of age).

label: Urine included in L:M analysis
definition: Flag for Lactulose:Mannitol (L:M) urine samples that were excluded from analysis. Reasons for exclusion include (i) if either lactulose or mannitol were not detected, (ii) if either lactulose or mannitol excretion was more than 100% of the dosage, (iii) if the duration of urine collection was either less than 4.5 hours or more than 5.5 hours, or (iv) if there was some other known issue with the sample. The Lactulose:Mannitol dual sugar test for gut permeability was used for analysis of environmental enteropathy and was assessed in urine samples collected at 3, 6, 9, and 15 months of age.

label: Stool type, physiologic
definition: Type of stool type collected, using information from surveillance. 'Diarrhea stools' were samples with a liquid or watery consistency where diarrhea was reported within +/- 2 days of stool collection. 'Monthly stools' were collected more than 2 days away from an episode of study-defined diarrhea. Surveillance was conducted twice weekly for up to 3 years of age to assess illness on all days since the last surveillance visit. Whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day, diarrheal stool samples were collected before the end of the episode. Work up for detection of enteric pathogens was performed on diarrheal stool samples collected until 24 months of age (with a possible extension to 36 months of age) and on first monthly asymptomatic stool samples collected at 1-12, 15, 18, 21, and 24 months of age (with the option to test additional monthly stool samples to 36 months of age).
codebook_description: Type of stool sample collected. Using information from surveillance. Diarrhea stool = diarrhea reported within +/- 2 days from stool collection plus having a liquid or watery consistency. Monthly stool is stool collected more than 2 days away from study defined diarrhea. Source=Calculated. m1 =monthly; d1=diarrhea stool with watery or liquid consistency

label: Cumulative sum Enterobius vermicularis-pos stools
definition: Cumulative sum of stool samples positive for Enterobius vermicularis by microscopy to date per participant. definition: The actual randomized, blinded intervention assigned to the cluster. The passive control arm enabled measurement of the effect of regular promoter visits in the active control arm. | The actual randomized, blinded intervention assigned to the compound. Compounds consisted of multiple households (typically 3 to 10 in Bangladesh), usually comprised of blood relatives, who share a common courtyard. Groups of 8 proximate compounds were assigned to a cluster, and each randomization block was made up of 8 adjacent clusters that were pair-matched by geography. Each cluster within the randomization block was randomly allocated to one of 7 study arms, including 2 clusters randomly allocated to the control arm. A description of each study arm can be found on the study details page. | Both arms were provided supplies to screen and treat syphilis. label: Time between diarrheal episodes
definition: Time (originally reported in days) until the next diarrheal episode starts (missing indicates time from last episode to end of follow-up, or from birth if the participant never had diarrhea during the follow-up period). Diarrhea episodes were separated by two diarrhea-free days. Days when data are missing were classified as diarrhea-free (if there were two missing days before a day with diarrhea, the episode started on day with diarrhea). Days with Lactulose:Mannitol (L:M)-induced diarrhea were classified as diarrhea-free. Surveillance was conducted twice weekly for up to 3 years of age to assess illness on all days since the last surveillance visit.
codebook_description: Days until next diarrhea starts (missing indicates time from last episode to end of follow up (or from birth if no diarrhea)), calculated. General diarrhea data (removes LM induced diarrhea).

label: Total time in all diarrheal episodes, excluding 1st days
definition: Total time (originally reported in days) falling within any diarrheal episode during follow-up, excluding the first day of each diarrheal episode. To calculate the time at risk for a new diarrheal episode, subtract 'Total days in all diarrheal episodes' from 'Total diarrheal surveillance days.' Diarrhea episodes were separated by two diarrhea-free days. Days when data were missing were classified as diarrhea-free (if there were two missing days before a day with diarrhea, the episode started on day with diarrhea). Days with Lactulose:Mannitol (L:M)-induced diarrhea were classified as diarrhea-free. Surveillance was conducted twice weekly for up to 3 years of age to assess illness on all days since the last surveillance visit.

label: Cluster as-treated, dichotomized
definition: The type of long-lasting insecticide-treated bednet (LLIN) received by the cluster during the 2016-2017 Universal Coverage Campaign (UCC), for the as-treated analysis. LLINs were distributed to clusters after the baseline survey was performed at the 0 month 'Study timepoint'. Clusters received either conventional LLINs or LLINs containing piperonyl butoxide (PBO). Conventional LLINs include PermaNet 2.0 and Olyset Net. PBO LLINs include PermaNet 3.0 and Olyset Plus. Certain clusters received a different LLIN type than that which was originally assigned to that cluster ('Cluster study arm'). For the as-treated analysis, clusters were grouped by type of LLINs received according to household data from the 6-month study timepoint ('UCC LLIN type'). For clusters with mixed LLIN distribution, the number of LLINs from the dominant type received was divided by the total number of LLINs received in that cluster; non-study nets were excluded. To be included in the as-treated analyses, the proportion of the dominant LLIN had to be more than 75%. 'Cluster as-treated' analyses were presented as the main study findings.
codebook_description: Intervention arm dichotomized for per protocol analysis

label: LNS consumed count
definition: Number of lipid-based nutrient supplement (LNS) sachets consumed by the household per week. LNS sachets were provided to study children as well as to older, age-eligible siblings (6 to 24 months) living in study households to prevent potential sharing of LNS with older siblings. Assessed at enrollment (year 0, pre-intervention baseline), 1 year after intervention initiation (midline) and 2 years after intervention initiation (endline). | Number of lipid-based nutrient supplement (LNS) sachets consumed by the household per week, based on counting sachets present at the time of a field visit. Housholds were only provided with LNS for target children because older, age-eligible siblings were rare in the study population. The expected number of sachets for 100% adherence is 14 sachets (7 days x 2 sachets per day). Values of LNS consumed that were negative or >28 were flagged.  Assessed for the household 1 year after intervention initiation (midline, when target children were 8-15m of age) and 2 years after intervention initiation (endline, when target children were 21-27m of age).

definition: Total time (originally reported in days) falling within any diarrheal episode since beginning of follow-up. Diarrhea episodes were separated by two diarrhea-free days. Surveillance was conducted twice weekly for up to 3 years of age to assess illness on all days since the last surveillance visit.

label: Percent LNS consumed, caregiver report
definition: Percent of expected lipid-based nutrient supplement (LNS) sachets consumed by the household, as reported by the mother. The expected number of sachets for 100% adherence is 14 sachets (7 days x 2 sachets per day). Assessed for the household 1 year after intervention initiation (midline, when target children were 8-15m of age) and 2 years after intervention initiation (endline, when target children were 21-27m of age). label: Stool test count
definition: Number of microbiology tests performed on this stool sample, including bacteriology culture; ELISAs for Campylobacter, Cryptosporidium, Giardia, Entamoeba histolytica, Adenovirus, Astrovirus, and Rotavirus; RT-PCR for Norovirus; PCR for Escherichia coli; wet prep microscopy (direct and concentrate); and modified acid fast stain microscopy. Note: E. coli PCR was not necessary if E. coli was not found in culture; however, E. coli PCR was still considered to be performed to determine the number of tests performed on the stool sample. Whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day, diarrheal stool samples were collected before the end of the episode. Work up for detection of enteric pathogens was performed on the first stool sample collected during each diarrheal episode until 24 months of age (with a possible extension to 36 months of age) and on first monthly asymptomatic stool samples collected at 1-12, 15, 18, 21, and 24 months of age (with the option to test additional monthly stool samples to 36 months of age).
codebook_description: number of microbiology tests performed on this specific stool sample. uses information from the FVF, ECP, BDF, MDF, NRV, PEF forms to determine number of tests performed on stool sample. If e. coli was not found in culture and therefore PCR was not necessary, e.coli PCR was still considered to be performed to determine number of tests. Repeat tests performed on initial and recollection stool samples are not counted twice.. Source=Calculated. continous numeric

definition: Cumulative sum of stool samples in which viruses ('Astrovirus, by ELISA;' 'Adenovirus, by ELISA;' 'Rotavirus, by ELISA;' 'Norovirus GI, by RT-PCR;' and/or 'Norovirus GII, by RT-PCR') were identified per participant to date. Complete testing of stool samples is required to calculate this variable. Includes information from first monthly asymptomatic stools collected for each month and first diarrheal stools collected for each diarrheal episode. Whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day, diarrheal stool samples were collected before the end of the episode. Work up for detection of enteric pathogens was performed on the first stool sample collected during each diarrheal episode until 24 months of age (with a possible extension to 36 months of age) and on first monthly asymptomatic stool samples collected at 1-12, 15, 18, 21, and 24 months of age (with the option to test additional monthly stool samples to 36 months of age).

Whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day, diarrheal stool samples were collected before the end of the episode. Work up for detection of enteric pathogens was performed on the first stool sample collected during each diarrheal episode until 24 months of age (with a possible extension to 36 months of age) and on first monthly asymptomatic stool samples collected at 1-12, 15, 18, 21, and 24 months of age (with the option to test additional monthly stool samples to 36 months of age).
codebook_description: Did this stool sample have a virus detected?. if astro =1 or nrvgeno1=1 or or nrvgeno2 =1 or rota=1 or adeno=1 then virus=1;else virus =0 /**allows for monthly stool sample to be positive if have positive NRV test result***/. Source=Calculated. 1=yes;0=no

label: Bacteriology testing completed
definition: Whether this stool sample underwent all bacteriology tests. Stool samples must have a completed Campylobacter ELISA test in addition to culture for Salmonella, Shigella, Vibrio, Yersinia, Aeromonas, and Plesiomonas for bacteriology testing to be considered complete. After culture, suspicious colonies were screened by biochemical tests to identify bacterial species. All presumptive Salmonella, Shigella, and Vibrio were confirmed by serotyping. Yersinia, Aeromonas, and Plesiomonas were confirmed by supplemental biochemical tests. Whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day, diarrheal stool samples were collected before the end of the episode. Work up for detection of enteric pathogens was performed on the first stool sample collected during each diarrheal episode until 24 months of age (with a possible extension to 36 months of age) and on first monthly asymptomatic stool samples collected at 1-12, 15, 18, 21, and 24 months of age (with the option to test additional monthly stool samples to 36 months of age).

label: Results from all gut inflammation tests available
definition: Whether results from alpha-1-antitrypsin, myeloperoxidase, and neopterin gut inflammation biomarker tests are available for the stool sample. label: Fully vaccinated for pneumococcal conjugate vaccine (PCV)
definition: Fully vaccinated for PCV. For children younger than 1 year, full vaccination was defined as having received at least one dose and being up to date for age on the basis of the child's age at enrollment, doses received, and country schedule (allowing a 4-week window for each dose); for children aged 1 year or older in all sites except Kenya, full vaccination was defined as having received three or more doses; for children older than 1 year in Kenya (which introduced PCV with catch-up campaign), full vaccination was defined as having received three or more doses, two doses if given at least 8 weeks apart and the child was older than 1 year of age at first dose, and one dose if the child was older than 2 years at any dose or at introduction.
codebook_description: Fully vaccinated for PCV. label: Cumulative sum unique pathogen (excluding NRV) in stools
definition: Cumulative sum of unique pathogen species (excluding Norovirus) identified in stool samples to date per participant. Complete testing of stool samples is required to calculate this variable. Includes information from first monthly asymptomatic stools collected for each month and all protocol-compliant diarrheal stools collected for each diarrheal episode (including additional diarrheal samples collected after 14 diarrhea days). Work up for detection of enteric pathogens was performed on diarrheal stool samples collected until 24 months of age (with a possible extension to 36 months of age) and on first monthly asymptomatic stool samples collected at 1-12, 15, 18, 21, and 24 months of age (with the option to test additional monthly stool samples to 36 months of age).

label: Lost to follow-up within 7 days of stool collection
definition: Whether the participant was lost to follow-up, but the length of time with surveillance data before or after stool collection was less than 7 days. This variable determines whether there was sufficient follow-up to create 'Stool type, 7 day window,' an alternative stool type definition. First monthly asymptomatic stool samples were collected every month from 0-24 months of age, with a possible extension to 36 months of age. Surveillance was conducted twice weekly for up to 3 years of age to assess illness on all days since the last surveillance visit. Whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day, diarrheal stool samples were collected before the end of the episode.

label: Cumulative sum ETEC LT-pos stools
definition: Cumulative sum of stool samples positive for Enterotoxigenic Escherichia coli (ETEC), as defined by the presence of heat-labile enterotoxin (LT) by PCR, to date per participant. Whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day, diarrheal stool samples were collected before the end of the episode. Work up for detection of enteric pathogens was performed on the first stool sample collected during each diarrheal episode until 24 months of age (with a possible extension to 36 months of age) and on first monthly asymptomatic stool samples collected at 1-12, 15, 18, 21, and 24 months of age (with the option to test additional monthly stool samples to 36 months of age).
codebook_description: cumulative count of the number of positive LT samples by PID. . Source=Calculated. continuous numeric

label: Polio serotype 1 seroconversion failure
definition: Seroconversion failure was derived based on the child's serum neutralizing antibodies (SNA) at 40 weeks (SNAwk40) and the maternal-antibody adjusted SNA at 18 weeks (SNAwk18). The participant was considered to have failed to seroconvert if a) SNAwk18 <= 2.833 and SNAwk40 <= 3 or b)  2.833 < SNAwk18 <= 8.5 and (SNAwk40 - SNAwk18) < 2 or c) 8.5 < SNAwk18 <10.5 and SNAwk40 < 10.5. Participants with SNAwk18  >= 10.5 were excluded.
codebook_description:
Sabin 1 seroconversion failure * 1.For subjects 2.833< SNAwk18_adjust <= 8.5
Seroconversion failure if (SNAwk40 - SNAwk18_adjust)<2
2.For subjects 8.5 < SNAwk18_adjust <10.5 
   Seroconversion failure if SNAwk40 < 10.5
3. For subjects SNAwk18_adjust <= 2.833
   Seroconversion failure if SNAwk40 <= 3
4. For subjects SNAwk18_adjust >= 10.5, excluded.

label: Stool type, gut function
definition: Stool type definition from the MAL-ED Gut Function Technical Subcommittee. 'Other stools' were samples where diarrhea was reported within the preceding 7 days and/or the lactulose:mannitol test was performed on the day of or day before stool collection. 'Asymptomatic stools' were stool samples that did not meet this definition of 'Other stools.' Only 'Asymptomatic stools' were included in the gut function analysis set used in PMID: 28396264. Surveillance was conducted twice weekly for up to 3 years of age to assess illness on all days since the last surveillance visit. Whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day, diarrheal stool samples were collected before the end of the episode. First monthly asymptomatic stool samples were collected every month from 0-24 months of age, with a possible extension to 36 months of age. First monthly asymptomatic stool samples collected at 1-12, 15, 18, 21, and 24 months of age were included in analyses of gut function.
codebook_description: gut function committee stool type definition 0 = asymptomatic; 1 if diarrhea within the preceding 7 days and/or LM test on the day of or day before stool collection. Source=calculated.

label: Referral, fieldworker assessment
definition: Whether the field worker referred the participant for medical care during the surveillance visit. The participant was referred to the nearest health center for assessment and treatment if: (i) their temperature was above 39C; (ii) they passed 8 or more loose stools in a 24 hour period; (iii) had blood in their stool; (iv) had severe dehydration; or (v) if the field worker determined that the participant had an acute lower respiratory infection (ALRI). Surveillance was conducted twice weekly for up to 3 years of age to assess illness on all days since the last surveillance visit.
